headline: 'The Five' break down the shutdown blame game
subHeadline: The federal government to shut down after midnight if Senate doesn't strike deal; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: We had a long and detailed meeting to discuss all of the major outstanding issues. We made some progress. We still have good number of (INAUDIBLE). Discussions will continue.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: As usual in Washington, plenty of blame going around on both sides.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I wish for all of our sakes that the Democratic leader would figure out what he actually wants.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The best that the Republican leader in the senate can offer us road is another band aid, another four weeks of temporary funding. A wasteful gesture, a wasteful exercise, and he knows it.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: So, what they're simply trying to do is hold all of government hostage. Our troops, kid's health insurance for a completely unrelated issue, and I think is shameful.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Democrats has been consistently been ready and willing to sit down at the negotiating table and reach an agreement with our Republican colleagues. But we will not be blackmailed.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. So, the Republican, Jesse, I'll go to you first. Very discipline on their message. We pass a clean C.R. There's nothing in there that you don't agree with. Why not just go ahead and do that and we'll keep talking to you about the other stuff?  JESSE WATTERS, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: I'm just bored by the whole thing. I think this country is run by imbeciles. We're $20 trillion in debts. We do this every single year. We spend more and more money on this government and it does less. The only thing that works in this government --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And the military. I know. Sometimes you shut it down and then nothing happens. And you think, ah, do we really need it? But the Democrats think they have leverage here because the polls are obviously going to turn against the Republicans. But, it looks like to me they're putting dreamers over the military. The military is not going to get paid, firefighters are not going to get paid, postmen aren't going to get paid, but I don't think congress should be paid because this is ridiculous. The American people are going to wake up on Saturday if they shut this down and say, OK, so how does this affect me? Every year we get involved with this silly drama. These politicians pull us into their silly drama and everybody with the countdown clock, it's ridiculous. I'm sick of it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: If this happened in a normal company and, you know, they had the quarterly deadline, it would never happen in the private sector. It only happens with these guys.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan, right before I came down, I saw -- there are Republicans saying that every Democrat senator who is running for reelection in a red state, and they're many of them, that they should have ads run against him this weekend and says, you are choosing illegal immigrants over a 800,000 children who would be funded with children's health insurance programs. Effective? JUAN WILLIAMS, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: No, there's just so much -- so easy to counter attack because, obviously, he could have passed the chip program, the children's health insurance plan, at any point and the Republicans didn't do it. And so, now you have a situation where you have Republican in the White House, Republican house, Republican senate, they have not been able to reach a deal. They can't pass a budget. So, we come back to then the argument about the dreamers. And you hear -- and Jesse just reacted to this. He says, oh, it's about the military or it's about something else. Guess what? It's all about President Trump causing chaos and people don't know how to deal with it. People don't know exactly what -- even Republican don't know exactly what it is that Donald Trump is willing to sign here. They thought they had a deal --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He's going to sign the budget, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, if that's the case then Republican has --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So why are you filibustering in the senate?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Nobody is filibustering --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sure you are.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, they not --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, you need 60 votes, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's right. That's not a filibuster, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me just say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You need to have four in the house?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, please.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Not the dreamers.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: This is not a spending issue. Dreamers have nothing to do with the budget.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me just say --  KIMBERLY GUILFOYLE, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: Jesse's not happy.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think it's close to 80 percent of Americans support the dreamers. Donald Trump, the president --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And then he open the negotiations, Greg. He said he was willing to make a deal.   GREG GUTFELD, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: It's not part of the spending thing. And you keep saying, oh, they have the house, they have the senate, we know you need 60 votes, so let's kill that argument.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I will say this, if you want to know who to blame. When the Democrats are in power when this happens, it's the Republicans. And when the Republicans are in power, it's the Republicans. So, if you noticed a trend here it's the Republicans' fault. But I will say this about the Republicans, the interior department, at least said you don't need staffing if there's going to be a shutdown. You can still have the open air memorials and you can have national parks open in case of a shutdown, you don't need staffing. So, unlike Obama, they didn't, like, use barricades to score emotional political points which makes me thinks maybe Republicans are better people.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Kimberly, earlier today, Secretary Mattis arrived at the defense department, did the national defense review, basically, and it was very stark. And this is what he had to say about the shutdown.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's got a huge morale impact. I will just tell you. How long can you keep good people around when something like this happens? It's always a question that's got to hover in the back of my mind. I would just tell you that we do a lot of intelligence operations around the world and they cost money. Those, obviously, would stop.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: K.G.?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yeah. The last thing you want to do -- I mean, honestly, as Jesse mention, a couple of things. I'm not going to cheer for the R.S., let me tell you. However, the military I cheer for. And when you see a situation like this and you hear someone speak about it like General Mattis, the last thing you want to do is jeopardize our national security and affect the moral there. And it just seems like it's just such political gamesmanship. And you know what? The American people can see through it. It's frustrating because they should put through this spending. There's no need to go through these kinds of machinations, whatsoever. But nevertheless, they persist. Danna: Yeah. And our enemies, Greg, this is what Mattis was talking about earlier, China, Russia, in particular, are fully funded. They can plan well ahead. They have everything that they need. And we are superior, but we've got to stay on top of things.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I mean, it goes back to the initial point. The Democrats are willing to shut down the government over a political cause. They will stop funding, things that are important to citizens of the United States over a political cause. They're willing, actually, to throw over one group of minorities for another group of minorities if it serves them politically. I have to say there's a little bit of progress here, and that is calling it the Schumer shutdown. It's a smart move because alliteration trumps everything. If you remember, the left tried to -- what they were calling Donald Trump? Donald Drump, it didn't work.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Because abstract cleverness --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The Democrats had better hashtags in the tax reform debate than the Republicans. But yes, Schumer shutdown was good. But then, I'm going to ask you, Jesse, Senator Schumer was invited by President Trump up to the White House, that neither of them have revealed what was said in the meetings. The only thing Schumer said that there was progress. What do you think they talked about?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They might have cooked up something where Trump comes in and saves the day, or Schumer comes in and saves the day. We'll see what happens. But Schumer and Pelosi they're doing right now the exact thing they accused Republicans are doing in 2013, which is being arsonists and hostage takers and shutting down the government for something totally unrelated to the budget --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, a lot of Republicans say that ultimately in the long run that the shutdown help them. So, Juan, Do you think that the Democrats are thinking that this is a possibility for them, too?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think that people are looking right now, Dana, and saying why does the government -- this is on top of what Jesse was saying, why does the government always get in the situation? Even Marc Short, the legislative director for the White House says this is a dysfunctional congress, and he's talking about that. So people are saying, well, you mean Republican and Democrats, well, obviously.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It would be great if we could get back to regular budgeting for everyone. It would be --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah. But I just can't take -- oh, yeah, yeah, you know why is this being brought in? Remember, this whole issue of DACA, so popular with the American people, was forced by Donald Trump, he created this crisis when he shut it down and said because I want a deal --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The facts are that this deal has been expanding. There were two continuing resolutions done in December on the premise that we'll make a deal in January.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The deadline was not for a while, Juan. They're trying to attach this cliffhanger to the budget.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You keep spinning.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's the truth. Let's spin.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So here's what happened. Then the president has the bipartisan deal, this is Monday, a week ago, and everybody comes together and says, here, we think we've got it. Come back Mr. President. They come back to him with a deal, a bipartisan deal. Republicans and Democrats --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Wrong.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There is no text of a bill about dreamers to vote on. There's nothing to vote on. There is no bill. They can't vote on something that's not --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: When they came back to the White House, when they came back to the president --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So you want to shut the government down. Juan wants to shut it down. We shouldn't call it the Schumer shutdown, we should call it the Juan shutdown.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Your way of dealing with things is to shout. You're very much like Trump. Trump is the one that Republicans can't even trust. He's the one who says, oh, yeah, don't put chip in the deal. Don't do that. We want a clean -- all of a sudden changes it back again --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Doesn't matter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Republican senators are on the record saying we don't have any reliable leadership or direction coming from this White House.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Want to know a little point of history?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: My first day on the job on Capitol Hill as the press secretary was the first day of the first government shutdown in 1995.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I hope you're not calling it right now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Talking about my shutdown woes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We should have another clock. See this clock right here? For the next shutdown, like, just move ahead. It's going to happen. Just this stupid clock.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Actually, it could be even this week if they get this C.R. done. All right, U.S. history made today in America's biggest annual pro-life rally, the march for life milestone, next.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: A big day for the pro-life movement in America. The 45th annual march for life was held in Washington, D.C., and for the very first time, a sitting president addressed the rally live. President Trump throwing his full support behind the demonstration to protect the sanctity of life. We have satellites from the White House rose garden.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.sentences: Under my administration, we will always defend the very first right in the declaration of independence and that is the right to life. We are protecting the sanctity of life and the family as the foundation of our society. That is why we march. That is why we pray. And that is why we declare that America's future will be filled with goodness, peace, joy, dignity, and life for every child of God.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Previous president like Ronald Reagan and George W. Bush address marches via phone call or a recorded message. Dana, so let's talk about that from a historical perspective.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, it's an amazing march. And I think -- was that you, Juan, that was at a hotel last year or the year before, and all the young people there that were for the march. It's a real moment for these young people who are pro-life supporters. They always get there. Thankfully the weather wasn't as bad as it usually is for them. But this corresponds with a time when you see that attitudes towards life are changing, and partly I think that is because of science. The science is starting to show that earlier and earlier, babies can be born and survive if they are born prematurely. And also, I think, that there's something to be said about all the benefits that we have from technology that are showing us what we might believe in our hearts is that life begins at conception. But now, you can actually see it more, and that's made a big difference.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: OK. Jesse, what did you think about this? Good to the address --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's a great address and a big victory for the pro-life movement to get a sitting president there live, obviously. And the evangelical movement and the pro-life movement have been very supportive of this president. And for someone that didn't really come from a very strong pro- life evangelical Christian background, he's really delivered on a number of levels for this movement.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: They really did help him during the campaign.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Exactly. Despite his background, they really did, especially in Iowa and in other places like that. He had Barron very late in his life. He wasn't always pro-life. He evolved as the chiefs of staff John Kelly would say on this issue, and has come to a pro-life decision. I think when you're older and you have children, it does really wakes you up. And you see that baby, or the fetus, as a life, and that's changed to him a person.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: All right, fantastic. OK, Juanito? You still have a quizzical look on your face.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I was listening to Jesse because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse, you kept talking about he has evolved as the chief of staff might say on other issue. On this issue, which is often to me, I just don't get why people who are strongly pro-life would say, oh, yeah, we're going to embrace this guy. This guy understands us. Well, this guy-- you know, in his heart -- No, it seems to me it's politically expedient for someone who is running on the Republican --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You don't know what's in his heart. He's had a child and he saw that child on the ultrasound --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. What I know is what's on the record, Jesse. And what's on the record is Donald Trump saying I am pro-choice, for most of his life. That's what the man said.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: President Obama evolved on gay marriage --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, here we go. You love to go to Obama every time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It's not the identical argument.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Actually, it's not as quite because you can imagine that President Obama, actually, didn't have a problem with gay marriage but said he did.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Even worse.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And then said they've evolved in order to explain the policy difference. I actually think when it comes to pro-life issue that you can have a change of heart for all sorts of reasons. Perhaps a religious one, or I was saying --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Including science.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The science one. I mean, the other thing is that the president is delivering on other things. For example, they just created this new office at the health and human services department that will deal with people who are working for the government and being able to respect their religious conscious on issues. In addition to that, the house today passed a bill called the born alive act, which would make that illegal. Kimberly, you know a little bit of that from the Gosnell trial. And I asked them today, do you have a plan to try to get it through the senate so the president can sign it, and they're hopeful.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: OK. Greg, so what do make of this?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Just over all, you know, a real protest movement, as far as I'm concern, is one that gives voice to the voiceless. So whether it's unborn children or women in Islamic regimes -- under Islamic regimes, these are the important protests that demand attention most, which are, ironically, the ones that liberal activists tend to avoid. They tend to avoid the protests where they truly are the voiceless. They favor instead, you know, pink hats.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I'm just going to say that. Remember those?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I mean, if you compare the media coverage of the march to life with the women's much, here you have one that represents no voice and you have one that represents many voices, many western voices. It reminds you that -- just the term pro-choice. If you have to redefine something as a choice, it's because you believe that there is a consequence for the other side of the choice, because if there was no consequence, you wouldn't be calling it a choice.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I would call it a choice for American women. And let me tell you. The voiceless is something like 78 percent of Americans think that there should be legal abortion in this country.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think women it's probably around 50-50 if I'm not clear. If I'm wrong, you can correct me. But it is. I will say, yeah, a lot of people do think abortion should be legal, even knowing that it's murder. It's an interesting moral state that we've come to that many people accept that abortion is murder, but still want it legal. That is part of the pro- choice idea. They're not denying it's murder. They're saying it's a choice.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, I don't consider it murder --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm very sensitive on this issue. I take it almost as a matter of Christian principles, so I'm very much concerned and thoughtful on it. But I see it as a matter of women and women having the right to control their reproductive right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, you know what, I'm not. I'm not religious. And I happen to believe that it is murder.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Not a woman.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: So, you can save your religion. I don't need a moral lecture to tell you what I think is something wrong.-

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All I was saying that I was sharing your concern.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: In a weird way, I felt that you weren't.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: That's a good discussion always on The Five, that's why everyone likes to watch the show. Ahead --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Is it?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I think so.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Ahead, a bombshell memo said to detail how far the DOJ and FBI allegedly went to surveil the Trump campaign. Some Republican demanding it release to the public immediately. Right back, stay with us.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: There's a classified memo now circulating around congress which reportedly reveals abuse of the FISA program by some Department of Justice and FBI officials who've been investigating the Trump campaign. Now, some Republican lawmakers are demanding that that memo be released to the public immediately. Here's one.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I'm reading it and it's a very succinct, straightforward memo. And there were a couple of times as I'm reading this thing where I'm just like shaking my head. You've got to be kidding me. I can't believe they did that. So, I think it's something that is really significant. I think that the American people need to see it. There's growing support in the house to make this public so that the American people can see it. And here's the thing, the memo is done in such a way where you can easily make it public. It's classified top secret, but there are sources and methods here.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Some on the right allege this could, quote, be worse than Watergate, end quote. But you know, I have a hunch, nowhere even close. So, let me go right away to the White House spokesman, Jesse Watters.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, OK.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: He meant that as a good thing, do you know that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I defer. I defer.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK. I haven't seen the memo.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, you haven't?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But by the sight of these congress been coming in, it better be good. The way they're acting like this thing is like Watergate, it better be good because I'm sick of all of these, you know, Benghazi, you know, exclusives, and it's like, really, that's it? This better be good. Let's assume it is what we think it is. And what we think it is is the Obama administration, the department of justice, and the FBI, along with the Hillary Clinton campaign, abused the power of the surveillance program and spied on the Trump campaign before and after the election ended some serious unmasking. Now, if that's true, some of these congressmen say that people are going to be fired and people are going to go to jail. Not only that, Comey knew, allegedly. That's what another congressman said. And this has the potential to stop the Mueller investigation in its tracks. You know, it could be all sizzle, no steak, but I've never seen congressmen act as apoplectic before.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: A few things. If it is what it is, then I think that they should ask the president to help them and declassify it. Also, I don't think that's enough. I think that they should ask the president -- and the president should maybe want to declassify the FISA application that led to this surveillance. And I think there's a reason that they haven't. And I think it's because, one, that's not a good practice necessarily because we have FISA warrants for a reason and to keep them secret because you're trying to catch bad guys. I don't know how all of this got caught up in it, but I would imagine that if the president wanted to declassify the FISA application and not just have it as an issue to bludgeon the Democrats with and the previous administration with and to try to muddy the waters of the Mueller investigation, he would release it. He has the power.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: This is a key point, I think. So Adam Schiff, the Democrat on the House Intel Committee has said pretty much that. That this is an effort, part of a continuing effort to muddy the waters, discredit Mueller, discredit the FBI because of the two agents who having an affair and they were texting, and also, then, to go after the FISA court and the issue of unmasking. But is there is something there, Kimberly Guilfoyle?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yes. I mean, because Adam Schiff says -- and he's trying to, like, cover it up. And he didn't leak it himself, which he loves to do. Then I think that it is significant, actually. It shows that he's already trying to spin it and trying to discredit it. So therefore, it must be good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Must be good?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: As a prosecutor, I'm telling you that. Because he's obviously already trying to dig in to say, "Oh, no, don't pay attention to it. This is just an effort" -- no. You're not fooling us. We're going to get it. And then we're going to decide ourselves.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But it was put together by Republicans. And what he's saying -- what Schiff is saying is this is misleading talking points that will damage our intelligence agencies.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Well, let's see.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: What do you make of this, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I remember, as a kid, there was this library near where I grew up, and they had, like -- there was, like, a box with a hole in it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And you used to be able to stick your hand in the box and feel what was in the box.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: That's terrible.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And guess what it is?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And guess what it is.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's what we're doing right now. We've got our hand in a box, and --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: How does it feel?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Schiff will feel something -- if you're a Democrat, you'll feel like, I don't know, like, a sponge. But if you're -- if you're on the right, you'll feel, like, a rock. You know? It's crazy. I think I would say to the viewers -- first, I'd say release the memo. If there's nothing there, there's nothing there. But to the viewers, when somebody tells you it's worse than Watergate, be prepared to be let down. So release it, but don't set your hopes too high on stuff like this. Because we've been around this block a million times with so many different stories. And if you jump on every one of these stories, you're going to break a hip.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I talked to a congressman that read it, and he said it's underwhelming. And it doesn't quite --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Everything in life is underwhelming except for President Trump.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But I think if -- but I think if the president was asked, like, "Will you release the underlying FISA application along with this -- "

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, he's not going to do that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO

utterances.sentences: What is this?

utterances.sentences: No, I don't think it's a gerbil. And --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: You really don't know?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I kind of do, but I wonder if anybody else does.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: If this was a gerbil and it belonged to Greg, it probably still wouldn't be here on video.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, you're next.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK, "Watters' World" is live this Saturday night at 8 p.m. Shutdown mania. We've got the Mooch. We've got Lou Dobbs, and we have Diamond and Silk, my favorite ladies, besides you two ladies, of course.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: This is terrible.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh!

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That was awful.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Didn't we use this already?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Allegedly on his cell phone. Hs says he wasn't on his cell phone, but --

utterances.speaker: PERINO

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: We had a long and detailed meeting to discuss all of the major outstanding issues. We made some progress. We still have good number of (INAUDIBLE). Discussions will continue.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: As usual in Washington, plenty of blame going around on both sides.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I wish for all of our sakes that the Democratic leader would figure out what he actually wants.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: The best that the Republican leader in the senate can offer us road is another band aid, another four weeks of temporary funding. A wasteful gesture, a wasteful exercise, and he knows it.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: So, what they're simply trying to do is hold all of government hostage. Our troops, kid's health insurance for a completely unrelated issue, and I think is shameful.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Democrats has been consistently been ready and willing to sit down at the negotiating table and reach an agreement with our Republican colleagues. But we will not be blackmailed.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. So, the Republican, Jesse, I'll go to you first. Very discipline on their message. We pass a clean C.R. There's nothing in there that you don't agree with. Why not just go ahead and do that and we'll keep talking to you about the other stuff? JESSE WATTERS, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: I'm just bored by the whole thing. I think this country is run by imbeciles. We're $20 trillion in debts. We do this every single year. We spend more and more money on this government and it does less. The only thing that works in this government --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And the military. I know. Sometimes you shut it down and then nothing happens. And you think, ah, do we really need it? But the Democrats think they have leverage here because the polls are obviously going to turn against the Republicans. But, it looks like to me they're putting dreamers over the military. The military is not going to get paid, firefighters are not going to get paid, postmen aren't going to get paid, but I don't think congress should be paid because this is ridiculous. The American people are going to wake up on Saturday if they shut this down and say, OK, so how does this affect me? Every year we get involved with this silly drama. These politicians pull us into their silly drama and everybody with the countdown clock, it's ridiculous. I'm sick of it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: If this happened in a normal company and, you know, they had the quarterly deadline, it would never happen in the private sector. It only happens with these guys.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan, right before I came down, I saw -- there are Republicans saying that every Democrat senator who is running for reelection in a red state, and they're many of them, that they should have ads run against him this weekend and says, you are choosing illegal immigrants over a 800,000 children who would be funded with children's health insurance programs. Effective? JUAN WILLIAMS, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: No, there's just so much -- so easy to counter attack because, obviously, he could have passed the chip program, the children's health insurance plan, at any point and the Republicans didn't do it. And so, now you have a situation where you have Republican in the White House, Republican house, Republican senate, they have not been able to reach a deal. They can't pass a budget. So, we come back to then the argument about the dreamers. And you hear -- and Jesse just reacted to this. He says, oh, it's about the military or it's about something else. Guess what? It's all about President Trump causing chaos and people don't know how to deal with it. People don't know exactly what -- even Republican don't know exactly what it is that Donald Trump is willing to sign here. They thought they had a deal --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He's going to sign the budget, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, if that's the case then Republican has --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So why are you filibustering in the senate?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Nobody is filibustering --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sure you are.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, they not --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, you need 60 votes, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's right. That's not a filibuster, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me just say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You need to have four in the house?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, please.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Not the dreamers.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: This is not a spending issue. Dreamers have nothing to do with the budget.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me just say -- KIMBERLY GUILFOYLE, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: Jesse's not happy.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think it's close to 80 percent of Americans support the dreamers. Donald Trump, the president --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And then he open the negotiations, Greg. He said he was willing to make a deal. GREG GUTFELD, "THE FIVE" CO-HOST: It's not part of the spending thing. And you keep saying, oh, they have the house, they have the senate, we know you need 60 votes, so let's kill that argument.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I will say this, if you want to know who to blame. When the Democrats are in power when this happens, it's the Republicans. And when the Republicans are in power, it's the Republicans. So, if you noticed a trend here it's the Republicans' fault. But I will say this about the Republicans, the interior department, at least said you don't need staffing if there's going to be a shutdown. You can still have the open air memorials and you can have national parks open in case of a shutdown, you don't need staffing. So, unlike Obama, they didn't, like, use barricades to score emotional political points which makes me thinks maybe Republicans are better people.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Kimberly, earlier today, Secretary Mattis arrived at the defense department, did the national defense review, basically, and it was very stark. And this is what he had to say about the shutdown.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: It's got a huge morale impact. I will just tell you. How long can you keep good people around when something like this happens? It's always a question that's got to hover in the back of my mind. I would just tell you that we do a lot of intelligence operations around the world and they cost money. Those, obviously, would stop.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: K.G.?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yeah. The last thing you want to do -- I mean, honestly, as Jesse mention, a couple of things. I'm not going to cheer for the R.S., let me tell you. However, the military I cheer for. And when you see a situation like this and you hear someone speak about it like General Mattis, the last thing you want to do is jeopardize our national security and affect the moral there. And it just seems like it's just such political gamesmanship. And you know what? The American people can see through it. It's frustrating because they should put through this spending. There's no need to go through these kinds of machinations, whatsoever. But nevertheless, they persist.

utterances.speaker: Danna
utterances.utterance: Yeah. And our enemies, Greg, this is what Mattis was talking about earlier, China, Russia, in particular, are fully funded. They can plan well ahead. They have everything that they need. And we are superior, but we've got to stay on top of things.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I mean, it goes back to the initial point. The Democrats are willing to shut down the government over a political cause. They will stop funding, things that are important to citizens of the United States over a political cause. They're willing, actually, to throw over one group of minorities for another group of minorities if it serves them politically. I have to say there's a little bit of progress here, and that is calling it the Schumer shutdown. It's a smart move because alliteration trumps everything. If you remember, the left tried to -- what they were calling Donald Trump? Donald Drump, it didn't work.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Because abstract cleverness --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The Democrats had better hashtags in the tax reform debate than the Republicans. But yes, Schumer shutdown was good. But then, I'm going to ask you, Jesse, Senator Schumer was invited by President Trump up to the White House, that neither of them have revealed what was said in the meetings. The only thing Schumer said that there was progress. What do you think they talked about?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They might have cooked up something where Trump comes in and saves the day, or Schumer comes in and saves the day. We'll see what happens. But Schumer and Pelosi they're doing right now the exact thing they accused Republicans are doing in 2013, which is being arsonists and hostage takers and shutting down the government for something totally unrelated to the budget --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, a lot of Republicans say that ultimately in the long run that the shutdown help them. So, Juan, Do you think that the Democrats are thinking that this is a possibility for them, too?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think that people are looking right now, Dana, and saying why does the government -- this is on top of what Jesse was saying, why does the government always get in the situation? Even Marc Short, the legislative director for the White House says this is a dysfunctional congress, and he's talking about that. So people are saying, well, you mean Republican and Democrats, well, obviously.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It would be great if we could get back to regular budgeting for everyone. It would be --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah. But I just can't take -- oh, yeah, yeah, you know why is this being brought in? Remember, this whole issue of DACA, so popular with the American people, was forced by Donald Trump, he created this crisis when he shut it down and said because I want a deal --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The facts are that this deal has been expanding. There were two continuing resolutions done in December on the premise that we'll make a deal in January.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The deadline was not for a while, Juan. They're trying to attach this cliffhanger to the budget.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You keep spinning.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's the truth. Let's spin.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So here's what happened. Then the president has the bipartisan deal, this is Monday, a week ago, and everybody comes together and says, here, we think we've got it. Come back Mr. President. They come back to him with a deal, a bipartisan deal. Republicans and Democrats --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wrong.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There is no text of a bill about dreamers to vote on. There's nothing to vote on. There is no bill. They can't vote on something that's not --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: When they came back to the White House, when they came back to the president --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So you want to shut the government down. Juan wants to shut it down. We shouldn't call it the Schumer shutdown, we should call it the Juan shutdown.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Your way of dealing with things is to shout. You're very much like Trump. Trump is the one that Republicans can't even trust. He's the one who says, oh, yeah, don't put chip in the deal. Don't do that. We want a clean -- all of a sudden changes it back again --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Doesn't matter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's in.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Republican senators are on the record saying we don't have any reliable leadership or direction coming from this White House.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. Want to know a little point of history?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: My first day on the job on Capitol Hill as the press secretary was the first day of the first government shutdown in 1995.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I hope you're not calling it right now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Talking about my shutdown woes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We should have another clock. See this clock right here? For the next shutdown, like, just move ahead. It's going to happen. Just this stupid clock.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Actually, it could be even this week if they get this C.R. done. All right, U.S. history made today in America's biggest annual pro-life rally, the march for life milestone, next.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: A big day for the pro-life movement in America. The 45th annual march for life was held in Washington, D.C., and for the very first time, a sitting president addressed the rally live. President Trump throwing his full support behind the demonstration to protect the sanctity of life. We have satellites from the White House rose garden.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
utterances.utterance: Under my administration, we will always defend the very first right in the declaration of independence and that is the right to life. We are protecting the sanctity of life and the family as the foundation of our society. That is why we march. That is why we pray. And that is why we declare that America's future will be filled with goodness, peace, joy, dignity, and life for every child of God.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Previous president like Ronald Reagan and George W. Bush address marches via phone call or a recorded message. Dana, so let's talk about that from a historical perspective.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, it's an amazing march. And I think -- was that you, Juan, that was at a hotel last year or the year before, and all the young people there that were for the march. It's a real moment for these young people who are pro-life supporters. They always get there. Thankfully the weather wasn't as bad as it usually is for them. But this corresponds with a time when you see that attitudes towards life are changing, and partly I think that is because of science. The science is starting to show that earlier and earlier, babies can be born and survive if they are born prematurely. And also, I think, that there's something to be said about all the benefits that we have from technology that are showing us what we might believe in our hearts is that life begins at conception. But now, you can actually see it more, and that's made a big difference.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: OK. Jesse, what did you think about this? Good to the address --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's a great address and a big victory for the pro-life movement to get a sitting president there live, obviously. And the evangelical movement and the pro-life movement have been very supportive of this president. And for someone that didn't really come from a very strong pro- life evangelical Christian background, he's really delivered on a number of levels for this movement.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: They really did help him during the campaign.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Exactly. Despite his background, they really did, especially in Iowa and in other places like that. He had Barron very late in his life. He wasn't always pro-life. He evolved as the chiefs of staff John Kelly would say on this issue, and has come to a pro-life decision. I think when you're older and you have children, it does really wakes you up. And you see that baby, or the fetus, as a life, and that's changed to him a person.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: All right, fantastic. OK, Juanito? You still have a quizzical look on your face.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I was listening to Jesse because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, you kept talking about he has evolved as the chief of staff might say on other issue. On this issue, which is often to me, I just don't get why people who are strongly pro-life would say, oh, yeah, we're going to embrace this guy. This guy understands us. Well, this guy-- you know, in his heart -- No, it seems to me it's politically expedient for someone who is running on the Republican --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You don't know what's in his heart. He's had a child and he saw that child on the ultrasound --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no, no. What I know is what's on the record, Jesse. And what's on the record is Donald Trump saying I am pro-choice, for most of his life. That's what the man said.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: President Obama evolved on gay marriage --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, here we go. You love to go to Obama every time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It's not the identical argument.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Actually, it's not as quite because you can imagine that President Obama, actually, didn't have a problem with gay marriage but said he did.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Even worse.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And then said they've evolved in order to explain the policy difference. I actually think when it comes to pro-life issue that you can have a change of heart for all sorts of reasons. Perhaps a religious one, or I was saying --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Including science.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The science one. I mean, the other thing is that the president is delivering on other things. For example, they just created this new office at the health and human services department that will deal with people who are working for the government and being able to respect their religious conscious on issues. In addition to that, the house today passed a bill called the born alive act, which would make that illegal. Kimberly, you know a little bit of that from the Gosnell trial. And I asked them today, do you have a plan to try to get it through the senate so the president can sign it, and they're hopeful.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: OK. Greg, so what do make of this?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Just over all, you know, a real protest movement, as far as I'm concern, is one that gives voice to the voiceless. So whether it's unborn children or women in Islamic regimes -- under Islamic regimes, these are the important protests that demand attention most, which are, ironically, the ones that liberal activists tend to avoid. They tend to avoid the protests where they truly are the voiceless. They favor instead, you know, pink hats.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I'm just going to say that. Remember those?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I mean, if you compare the media coverage of the march to life with the women's much, here you have one that represents no voice and you have one that represents many voices, many western voices. It reminds you that -- just the term pro-choice. If you have to redefine something as a choice, it's because you believe that there is a consequence for the other side of the choice, because if there was no consequence, you wouldn't be calling it a choice.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I would call it a choice for American women. And let me tell you. The voiceless is something like 78 percent of Americans think that there should be legal abortion in this country.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think women it's probably around 50-50 if I'm not clear. If I'm wrong, you can correct me. But it is. I will say, yeah, a lot of people do think abortion should be legal, even knowing that it's murder. It's an interesting moral state that we've come to that many people accept that abortion is murder, but still want it legal. That is part of the pro- choice idea. They're not denying it's murder. They're saying it's a choice.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, I don't consider it murder --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm very sensitive on this issue. I take it almost as a matter of Christian principles, so I'm very much concerned and thoughtful on it. But I see it as a matter of women and women having the right to control their reproductive right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know what, I'm not. I'm not religious. And I happen to believe that it is murder.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Not a woman.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So, you can save your religion. I don't need a moral lecture to tell you what I think is something wrong.-

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All I was saying that I was sharing your concern.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: In a weird way, I felt that you weren't.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: That's a good discussion always on The Five, that's why everyone likes to watch the show. Ahead --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Is it?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I think so.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Ahead, a bombshell memo said to detail how far the DOJ and FBI allegedly went to surveil the Trump campaign. Some Republican demanding it release to the public immediately. Right back, stay with us.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There's a classified memo now circulating around congress which reportedly reveals abuse of the FISA program by some Department of Justice and FBI officials who've been investigating the Trump campaign. Now, some Republican lawmakers are demanding that that memo be released to the public immediately. Here's one.

utterances.speaker: UNINDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I'm reading it and it's a very succinct, straightforward memo. And there were a couple of times as I'm reading this thing where I'm just like shaking my head. You've got to be kidding me. I can't believe they did that. So, I think it's something that is really significant. I think that the American people need to see it. There's growing support in the house to make this public so that the American people can see it. And here's the thing, the memo is done in such a way where you can easily make it public. It's classified top secret, but there are sources and methods here.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Some on the right allege this could, quote, be worse than Watergate, end quote. But you know, I have a hunch, nowhere even close. So, let me go right away to the White House spokesman, Jesse Watters.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, OK.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: He meant that as a good thing, do you know that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I defer. I defer.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. I haven't seen the memo.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, you haven't?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: But by the sight of these congress been coming in, it better be good. The way they're acting like this thing is like Watergate, it better be good because I'm sick of all of these, you know, Benghazi, you know, exclusives, and it's like, really, that's it? This better be good. Let's assume it is what we think it is. And what we think it is is the Obama administration, the department of justice, and the FBI, along with the Hillary Clinton campaign, abused the power of the surveillance program and spied on the Trump campaign before and after the election ended some serious unmasking. Now, if that's true, some of these congressmen say that people are going to be fired and people are going to go to jail. Not only that, Comey knew, allegedly. That's what another congressman said. And this has the potential to stop the Mueller investigation in its tracks. You know, it could be all sizzle, no steak, but I've never seen congressmen act as apoplectic before.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: A few things. If it is what it is, then I think that they should ask the president to help them and declassify it. Also, I don't think that's enough. I think that they should ask the president -- and the president should maybe want to declassify the FISA application that led to this surveillance. And I think there's a reason that they haven't. And I think it's because, one, that's not a good practice necessarily because we have FISA warrants for a reason and to keep them secret because you're trying to catch bad guys. I don't know how all of this got caught up in it, but I would imagine that if the president wanted to declassify the FISA application and not just have it as an issue to bludgeon the Democrats with and the previous administration with and to try to muddy the waters of the Mueller investigation, he would release it. He has the power.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: This is a key point, I think. So Adam Schiff, the Democrat on the House Intel Committee has said pretty much that. That this is an effort, part of a continuing effort to muddy the waters, discredit Mueller, discredit the FBI because of the two agents who having an affair and they were texting, and also, then, to go after the FISA court and the issue of unmasking. But is there is something there, Kimberly Guilfoyle?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yes. I mean, because Adam Schiff says -- and he's trying to, like, cover it up. And he didn't leak it himself, which he loves to do. Then I think that it is significant, actually. It shows that he's already trying to spin it and trying to discredit it. So therefore, it must be good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Must be good?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: As a prosecutor, I'm telling you that. Because he's obviously already trying to dig in to say, "Oh, no, don't pay attention to it. This is just an effort" -- no. You're not fooling us. We're going to get it. And then we're going to decide ourselves.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But it was put together by Republicans. And what he's saying -- what Schiff is saying is this is misleading talking points that will damage our intelligence agencies.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Well, let's see.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What do you make of this, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I remember, as a kid, there was this library near where I grew up, and they had, like -- there was, like, a box with a hole in it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Oh, my gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And you used to be able to stick your hand in the box and feel what was in the box.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: That's terrible.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And guess what it is?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And guess what it is.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's what we're doing right now. We've got our hand in a box, and --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: How does it feel?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Schiff will feel something -- if you're a Democrat, you'll feel like, I don't know, like, a sponge. But if you're -- if you're on the right, you'll feel, like, a rock. You know? It's crazy. I think I would say to the viewers -- first, I'd say release the memo. If there's nothing there, there's nothing there. But to the viewers, when somebody tells you it's worse than Watergate, be prepared to be let down. So release it, but don't set your hopes too high on stuff like this. Because we've been around this block a million times with so many different stories. And if you jump on every one of these stories, you're going to break a hip.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I talked to a congressman that read it, and he said it's underwhelming. And it doesn't quite --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Everything in life is underwhelming except for President Trump.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But I think if -- but I think if the president was asked, like, "Will you release the underlying FISA application along with this -- "

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, he's not going to do that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, he might, and then that way it would be clear and everybody would know everything.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's all emo. With an "M."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think we see a lot of conspiracy theories on the right, though. "The Fastest Seven -- "

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: None on the left either, right?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God. How convenient. OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Time for --

utterances.speaker: GRAPHIC
utterances.utterance: Fastest 7

utterances.utterance: How do you think Trump has done in his first year in office?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Great.

utterances.utterance: What do you think he's done that's so great?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: He saved the world? From what?

utterances.utterance: Can you do an impression of the president for us?

utterances.utterance: You're fired!

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That took a while.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It does say one thing. I mean, these kids, 15 percent of their life has been lived under Trump. He's kind of, like, the most famous person in their lives, you know? It's like Evil Santa to them. But --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Dana, what'd you think?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I love -- oh, I wish I could hear what she's saying. I always love these things with the kids. I don't like it so much with the adults when they're making fun of them, you know, like, for not knowing stuff?

utterances.utterance: You mean, like, what I did?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. So Dana doesn't like "Watters' World." Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: She's not taking it back.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I would feel bad -- I would just feel bad for people.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. I know, you're very sensitive.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, I am.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And that's good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Are the two of you OK?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, we're OK. Move it along.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I like -- I like the whole theory because I remember what Art Linklater used to do --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- "Kids Say the Darndest Things," And I thought, for example, it was so surprising, when the kid said, "What did they save us from?" "Harmony." I was like, whoa, that's pretty funny. Did the kids set that up, or did he not know what he was doing?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I think it's pretty authentic. I didn't think this is staged.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: No, but it was so cute. I mean, I thought all of them were very funny. I like it. Like, "You're fired," all of them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't think it's cute.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Well, no one's asking you what I think?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm so tired of people go, "Oh, isn't he so cute? Oh, isn't it adorable when children say things?" No, it's not! It's an old idea.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Dumb.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Speaking of adorable.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yes, roll over.

utterances.utterance: Hot.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, Kimberly. Pretty good shape for the Russian president.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yes. I'm, you know, squinting a bit to check it all out. But-- from this distance. Yes, but you know, he's got -- when he has an opportunity to go "GQ," he does.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: So there you go. Let Putin be Putin.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Never miss an opportunity to be "GQ," right, Juan?

utterances.utterance: Well, you know, I don't know about him showing off how masculine he is, but I must say, taking the polar plunge there, that's pretty wild. Did he have his hands on while he's doing this? Is that --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.utterance: I didn't wonder that, really.

utterances.utterance: It looks like he's --

utterances.utterance: He put on, like, those big Uggs when he got out.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He's not -- but if you go out to Coney Island, those people are actually in bathing suits.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know. Well, you've got to cover it up. He was responding to the Trump health report. He was, like, "No, I'm the macho guy."

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: "I don't need a doctor. I will show you."

utterances.utterance: What did you think I was thinking?

utterances.utterance: Not sure where you're going with that.

utterances.utterance: It could be.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: That sounds like you're not saying no.

utterances.utterance: You'd need some crack. You know what? Trump broke the seal, and we've already seen Hulk's sex tape. So what could be worse than that, if you've seen it?

utterances.utterance: I guess you watched it.

utterances.utterance: A number of times to prepare for this show. If a sex scandal breaks, so what? I mean, and also, his best win was not in the ring. It was in court against Gawker.

utterances.utterance: That's right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We'll be right back.

utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.utterance: I'm thinking Republican.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Are the Democrats nervous in Florida, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't see why. But I mean, he sounds like a fun guy. Now, the reason I say I don't know if Democrats are nervous is because he backed Obama, then he backed Romney. So I guess he's moving towards the GOP But when that interview kept going, by the way, and he was asked, "What do you really want to run for?" he said he'd like to run for the wrestling championship again. So maybe that's where his heart is.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.utterance: Oh, my Gosh.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: We'll see.

utterances.utterance: All right. She's going to volunteer for the campaign, I think. "Facebook Friday" when "The Five" returns.

utterances.utterance: Yes. Juan, how about you? Any special --

utterances.utterance: It's quite a delightful sport, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Winter Olympics, I'm going to go with skiing. I'm a halfway decent skier. And then Summer Olympics, swimming. Because that was my strongest --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Stroke? I can't swim.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You can't swim?

utterances.utterance: I'll stick with winter. I'll say the luge.

utterances.utterance: The luge, eh?

utterances.utterance: Because you don't really have to do anything. I mean, forgive me--

utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wow, did you hear that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The luge audience is going --

utterances.utterance: Send her an e-mail.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I mean, because I don't weigh that much. So then I would just, like, go fast.

utterances.utterance: That is true.

utterances.utterance: Not really.

utterances.utterance: So Winter Olympics, I would pick for me shrinking. All right. Diane --

utterances.utterance: Wait, what are you talking about?

utterances.utterance: We'll go to Dana. "You've been kidnapped."

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.utterance: Yes. This is, like, a "Taken" scenario. "The last person you watched on TV is trying to save you. Who is it?"

utterances.utterance: She's a tough lady.

utterances.utterance: Yes, well, at least -- when she has guards, too.

utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So that would be beneficial.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. What about you, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That would be Jake Tapper. Because we were watching CNN in the green room.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, he has strong arms.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Hey, I'll take it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Caring eyes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Save me, Jake.

utterances.utterance: Jake -- "Tapper." Tonight at 9 after "MacGyver." Jesse -- I mean, Juan.

utterances.utterance: Oh, well, I guess -- I guess it would have to be Jesse.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes?

utterances.utterance: Wait. I'm not saving you anymore.

utterances.utterance: Oh, you're just going to hurt my feelings?

utterances.utterance: Yes. Wait, you're the hostage taker, remember? The shutdown.

utterances.utterance: Kimberly, last person you saw on TV is going to try to save you you?

utterances.utterance: Well I mean, I mean, I hope he would save me. But Cavuto?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Anyway, I was a victim of (ph) him. Kidnapping.

utterances.utterance: Good luck with that.

utterances.utterance: So they'd have to save me. They'd have to come in their little rescue van.

utterances.utterance: It will be just like Scooby Doo, the Kars4Kids.

utterances.utterance: Yes, exactly. Last question, I guess, right? -- from Patty P.: "Would love to know what all the papers say that are in front of everyone." Jesse.

utterances.utterance: Mine says "Jesse." That's it. That's all I've got.

utterances.utterance: Juan.

utterances.utterance: What you have in front of you when you're -- what do you?

utterances.utterance: All right. I have this. Yes. Yes. What? Show them my notes?

utterances.utterance: Yes. "One More Thing" next.

utterances.utterance: Now you're in trouble. Oh, my God.
